<p>A typical 6kW residential solar system in Rhode Island produces approximately 7,200-7,800 kWh annually, enough to offset most average households' electricity consumption. South-facing roofs with slopes between 30-40 degrees achieve optimal production, though east and west-facing installations still capture 85-90% of maximum potential. The state's net metering policies allow excess production during peak sun hours to offset evening and winter consumption, making solar financially viable even with seasonal variations.</p>

