<h2>HVAC Systems in Rhode Island</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Rhode Island's humid continental climate demands HVAC systems capable of handling both cold winters and warm, humid summers. Winter temperatures frequently drop into the 20s and 30s Fahrenheit, requiring reliable heating systems, while summer temperatures in the 70s and 80s combined with high humidity create substantial cooling loads. The state's coastal influence moderates temperature extremes but increases humidity levels, making proper dehumidification a critical component of any HVAC system design.</p>

<p>For Rhode Island homes, heat pumps with backup heating provide optimal year-round efficiency, particularly newer cold-climate models that maintain efficiency down to -15¬∞F. Air conditioning systems should feature SEER ratings of at least 16, with 18-20+ SEER systems providing the best long-term value given the state's high electricity rates. Proper humidity control is essential, with whole-house dehumidification systems often recommended to maintain indoor comfort during Rhode Island's humid summer months.</p>

